'''Albuquerque Civic Auditorium''' was an indoor arena in [[Albuquerque, New Mexico]]. It opened in 1957, and was demolished in 1987. It was notable for its innovative construction, as the dome was created by pouring concrete over a mound of packed earth that was subsequently removed. The auditorium was located east of [[Downtown Albuquerque|Downtown]] on Grand Avenue (now Dr. Martin Luther King Jr. Ave.), between St. Joseph Hospital and [[Interstate 25 in New Mexico|Interstate 25]]. It opened in 1957 and had a capacity of 6,000 people.
==History== The Albuquerque Civic Auditorium was designed by the Albuquerque firm of Ferguson, Stevens and Associates in 1955. Architects Gordon Ferguson and Donald Stevens came up with the idea of using an earthen mound as a form for the poured-in-place concrete dome.<ref>{{cite news | title=Civic Auditorium Designs Follow Modernist Trend| newspaper=Albuquerque Journal | date=April 22, 1955| location=NM | page=36}}</ref> An existing hill on the site was built up and shaped to the proper dimensions, followed by a ten-day concrete pour. The earth was then excavated from under the dome to create the arena space. The finished dome was {{convert|62|ft|m}} high, {{convert|218|ft|m}} in diameter, and varied in thickness from {{convert|5|in|cm}} at the center to {{convert|2|ft|cm}} at the edges.<ref>{{cite journal | title=Mound-Made Auditorium | journal=Life | date=June 10, 1957 | volume=42 | issue=23 | page=58}}</ref> The innovative construction technique garnered a mention in ''[[Life (magazine)|Life]]'' and was also praised by [[Frank Lloyd Wright]] during a lecture at the [[University of New Mexico]] in 1956.<ref>{{cite news | last=Mahoney | first=Jane | title=The First 60 Years | newspaper=Albuquerque Journal | date=November 29, 2004 | location=NM}}</ref>
The venue opened on April 27, 1957, with a performance by the [[Albuquerque Civic Symphony]].<ref name=Info>[http://www.ledzeppelin-database.com/geekbaseweb/forumpage.aspx?g=posts&t=34 Venue information and background]</ref> Over the years the venue hosted a number of notable acts, including [[Led Zeppelin]] in 1969 and [[Jimi Hendrix]] in 1970, just three months before his death.<ref>{{cite news | last=Herrera | first=Dan | title=Musician recorded '60s music scene | newspaper=Albuquerque Journal | date=January 1, 1999 | location=NM | page=E13}}</ref> It was also the home venue of the [[University of Albuquerque|University of Albuquerque Dons]] basketball team from 1963 to 1969.<ref>{{cite news | title=St. Joseph's to Buy Portable Gym Floor for Use in Auditorium | url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/18263225/albuquerque_journal/ | accessdate=March 13, 2018 | work=Albuquerque Journal | date=November 16, 1963 | via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> However, the auditorium had poor acoustics and eventually fell from popularity as a music venue in favor of [[Tingley Coliseum]] and Popejoy Hall.<ref>{{cite news|last=Palmer |first=Mo |title=Albuquerque's Civic Auditorium went from a landmark to the dustbin of history |url=http://www.abqtrib.com/news/2008/feb/14/mo-palmer-albuquerques-civic-auditorium-went-landm/ |accessdate=June 27, 2011 |newspaper=Albuquerque Tribune |date=February 14, 2008 |location=NM |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111112131214/http://www.abqtrib.com/news/2008/feb/14/mo-palmer-albuquerques-civic-auditorium-went-landm/ |archivedate=November 12, 2011 }}</ref> It was demolished in 1987.
