{{Other uses|Canadian Commonwealth Games (disambiguation){{!}}Canadian Commonwealth Games}} {{infobox country at games | CGA = CAN | CGAname = [[Commonwealth Games Canada]] | games = Commonwealth Games | year = | flagcaption = | oldcode = | website = {{url|commonwealthgames.ca }} | location = | competitors = | sports = | flagbearer = | rank = 3 | gold = 484 | silver = 516 | bronze = 555 | officials = | app_begin_year = | app_end_year = | seealso = {{flagCGF|NEW}} ([[Newfoundland at the 1930 British Empire Games|1930]], [[Newfoundland at the 1934 British Empire Games|1934]]) }} '''Canada''' has participated in every '''[[Commonwealth Games]]''' since the [[1930 British Empire Games|first ever British Empire Games]] held in [[Hamilton, Ontario]] in 1930, one of only six countries to have done so. The others are [[Australia at the Commonwealth Games|Australia]], [[England at the Commonwealth Games|England]], [[New Zealand at the Commonwealth Games|New Zealand]], [[Scotland at the Commonwealth Games|Scotland]], and [[Wales at the Commonwealth Games|Wales]].
== History == '''[[Dominion of Newfoundland|Newfoundland]]''' competed separately at the [[1930 British Empire Games|1930]] and [[1934 British Empire Games|1934]] Games (although not winning any medals), but since [[1950 British Empire Games|1950]] has competed as part of Canada.
The Canadian team won 54 medals in the [[1930 British Empire Games|first (1930) Games]], and 51 gold medals at [[1986 Commonwealth Games|Edinburgh (1986)]]. Canada's biggest total medal tally was 129 medals in [[1994 Commonwealth Games|Victoria (1994)]].
Canada came third in the medal count at the [[2006 Commonwealth Games]] in [[Melbourne]] after Australia and England, and is third on the [[all-time medal tally of Commonwealth Games]], with an overall total of 1318 medals (413 Gold, 443 Silver and 462 Bronze). Canada was top of the medal tally once, at the [[1978 Commonwealth Games|1978 games]] at [[Edmonton, Alberta]]
Canada has hosted the games four times. The first Games were at [[Hamilton, Ontario]] in 1930. [[Vancouver]] hosted the [[1954 British Empire and Commonwealth Games]] notable for the famous "miracle mile" ([[four-minute mile]]) between [[Roger Bannister]] of [[England]] and [[John Landy]] of Australia at [[Empire Stadium, Vancouver|Empire Stadium]]. [[Edmonton, Alberta|Edmonton]] was the first city to host the [[1978 Commonwealth Games|Commonwealth Games under that name in 1978]], and [[Victoria, British Columbia]] hosted the [[1994 Commonwealth Games|Games in 1994]].
Hamilton applied to host the [[2010 Commonwealth Games]] but lost to the [[Delhi]] bid. [[Halifax Regional Municipality|Halifax, Nova Scotia]] withdrew its [[Halifax 2014 Commonwealth Games bid|bid]] for the [[2014 Commonwealth Games]].
The Commonwealth Games Association in Canada, known as [[Commonwealth Games Canada]] (CGC) is responsible for organizing the Canadian team participating in the Commonwealth Games.
