{{Infobox sportsperson | headercolor = lightblue | name = Philip Elhage | image = | imagesize = | caption = | birth_name = | fullname = | nickname = | nationality = {{NLD}} | residence = | birth_date = {{birth date and age|1982|4|11|df=yes}} | birth_place = [[Curaçao]], Willemstad | death_date = | death_place = | height = {{height|m=1.72|abbr=on}} | weight = {{convert|65|kg|lb|0|abbr=on}} | website = | country = | sport = [[Shooting sport|Shooting]] | event = 10 m air pistol ([[AP60]]) | collegeteam = | club = Trigger Shooting Club<ref name=issf/> | team = | turnedpro = | coach = Shaheen Elhage<ref name=issf>{{cite web|title=ISSF Profile – Philip Elhage|url=http://www.issf-sports.org/athletes/athlete.ashx?personissfid=SHAHOM1104198201|publisher=[[International Shooting Sport Federation|ISSF]]|accessdate=11 January 2013}}</ref> | retired = | coaching = | worlds = | regionals = | nationals = | olympics = | paralympics = | highestranking = | pb = | medaltemplates = | show-medals = yes }}
'''Philip Elhage''' (born April 11, 1982 in [[Curaçao]]) is a Dutch [[Shooting sport|sport shooter]].<ref>{{cite sports-reference|Philip Elhage|https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/athletes/el/philip-elhage-1.html|11 January 2013}}</ref> Elhage represented the [[Netherlands Antilles]] at the [[2008 Summer Olympics]] in [[Beijing]], where he competed in the [[Shooting at the 2008 Summer Olympics - Men's 10 metre air pistol|men's 10 m air pistol]]. He finished only in forty-sixth place by two points behind Turkey's [[Yusuf Dikeç]] from the fourth attempt, for a total score of 566 targets.<ref>{{cite web|title=Men's 10m Air Pistol Qualification |url=http://www.2008.nbcolympics.com/shooting/resultsandschedules/rsc=SHM203901/index.html |publisher=[[NBC Olympics]] |accessdate=11 January 2013 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120816053200/http://www.2008.nbcolympics.com/shooting/resultsandschedules/rsc%3DSHM203901/index.html |archivedate=16 August 2012 |df= }}</ref>
